  "answer": "Both Manu and Yājñavalkya enumerate the same canonical four vācika (verbal) sins in their karma-cosmology sections. Manu (Mn_12.6, unknown-manusmrti-347b76 ch. 12) lists: harshness, falsehood, slander of all kinds, and irrelevant talk. Yājñavalkya (Yj_3.135, unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6 ch. 3) lists: untruth, slander, harsh speech, and idle talk — effectively the same four items in different order.\n\nThe asymmetry emerges when each text's fuller treatment is examined:\n\nIN MANU BUT NOT YĀJÑAVALKYA: Manu's penance chapter (Mn_11.55, ch. 12 file) elevates three specific verbal acts to the most severe tier — equal in gravity to brahmin-slaying: (1) false boasting (claiming ritual/Vedic credentials one does not possess), (2) slander that reaches the king (politically escalated defamation), and (3) false accusation against a guru. A second tier (Mn_11.56, [p-77c6f2]) names reviling the Veda and giving false testimony as verbal sins equivalent to drinking liquor. None of these appear in Yājñavalkya's penance chapter (ch. 3) as named verbal sins with specific penalties.\n\nIN YĀJÑAVALKYA BUT NOT MANU: Yājñavalkya's conduct chapter (Yj_1.33, ch. 1, [p-6a6d01]) names obscene speech as a prohibited verbal act for the student, alongside slander. This category does not appear in Manu's formal verbal sin lists.\n\nWhat the asymmetry tells us about social anxieties:\n\nManu's unique verbal sins are all hierarchically and politically charged. False boasting protects the exclusivity of Brahmanical status — in a world where ritual credentials conferred enormous social capital, fraudulent speech claims threatened the entire varna order. Slander that reaches the king protects royal authority as a second pillar of the social structure; Manu is deeply invested in the brahmin-king dyad. False accusation of a guru protects the guru-disciple relationship as the transmission mechanism of Vedic knowledge. Reviling the Veda and false testimony extend this anxiety: the Veda is cosmic truth, testimony is social truth, and both must be inviolate. Manu's anxiety is about speech as a social weapon that can erode hierarchy, corrupt power, and destabilize the ritual order from which Brahmanical authority flows.\n\nYājñavalkya's unique addition (obscene speech) reflects a different register of anxiety: the ritual-spiritual purity of the student's inner world. The brahmacharī must avoid words that arouse desire because sexual impurity is ritual impurity. This fits Yājñavalkya's overall orientation as a more yogically-inclined text — Yājñavalkya is repeatedly styled 'the lord of yogis' and chapter 3 culminates in liberation philosophy, not social-legal taxonomy. The anxiety here is not about speech destabilizing the social order but about speech contaminating the self that seeks liberation.",
